1... f6 { Trapping the bishop but the following try had to be calculated. } 2.
Ng6 { 14.exf6  gxf6  -+  transposes. } 2... Qxb2
{ Initiating a forced series of trades, after which the g6-knight will be lost.   14...fxg5  15.Nxh8  g4  16.Re3  Nf5  17.Ne2  Qxb2  18.Rb1  ∓  is also better for Black, but not nearly as good as the main line. }
3. Rb1
{ 15.Nxh8  Qxa1+  -+   15.Rc1  fxg5  16.Nxh8   16.Rc2  Qa1+  -+  16...Qxc1+  -+ }
3... Rxc3
{ 15...Qxc3+  is clearly weaker. After  16.Qxc3  Rxc3  17.Rxc3  Nxg6  18.Bd2  the only difference to the mainline is that White's rook is on c3 instead of d3. A minor detail that matters a lot. Whit the active rook on c3 White's rooks put a lot of pressure on Black's queenside and king, which is good enough for equality.  b6  19.Rc8+ !  Ke7  20.Rc7 !  Kd8  21.Ra7  fxe5  22.Rc1 ! = }
4. exf6 gxf6
{ 16...Rxd3 ??  spoils the win  17.f7+ !  Kxf7  18.Nxh8+  Kg8  19.Rxb2 = } 5.
Rxb2 Rxd3 6. Rxd3 Nxg6
{ Compared to 15... Qxc3 now White's rook is passive on d3 and Black can easily protect his queenside and finish development with e.g. b6 followed by Bd6. Additionally he can win another pawn hanging on h4. Black is completely winning. }
*

