1... Bxc2
{ This looks very convincing on first sight, but the combination is very deep and Black has to see everything before commiting to Bxc2. }
2. Qxc2 { 13.Nxc2  Bxe3  14.Nxe3  Qxe3  -+  just wins a pawn for Black. } 2...
Bb4+ 3. Kd1
{ 14.Kf2  is refuted more easily.  Rxc2  15.Nxc2  Bc5  16.Nxc5  Nxc5  Here this is possible, since after  17.b4  Black has  (Ne4+ -+)   14.Kf1  is the same as Kd1 }
3... Rxc2 4. Nxc2 Bc5 5. Nxc5 Nf5
{ This had to be spotted before taking on c2. Without this move Black would be clearly worse.   16...Nxc5 ??  17.b4  +-  White has too much material for the queen  White has a lot of tries now, but nothing works. }
6. Bf2
{ 17.Nxd7  Nxe3+  18.Nxe3   18.Kd2  is another line that is hard to judge from afar.  Kxd7  19.Nxe3  Qb4+  20.Kd3  Qe4+  21.Kd2  Qxf4  22.Rhf1  Qb4+  23.Kd3  Rc8  -+  18...Qxe3  -+  The knight on d7 is trapped.   17.b4  isn't really protecting c5.  Nxe3+  18.Nxe3  Nxc5  -+ }
6... Nxc5 7. b4 { So where is the big difference to 16... Nxc5 now ? } 7... d4
{ This is it. White can't take on c5 since b1 is hanging and after   19.Nxd4  Nxd4  20.Bxd4  Qd8  keeps Black's material advantage. }
