1. Bxh6
{ This is a common idea in Isolated-Queenspawn positions, but here is has an unusual twist. }
1... gxh6 { 18...Nxc3  transposes } 2. Qxh6 Nxc3
{ The most tricky reply. White has difficulties reinforcing his attack. } 3.
bxc3 { 20.Rd3 ??  Ne2+  -+ } 3... Rxc3
{ After other moves White has a deadly rook rover with Rd3, but what to do now with White ? }
4. Qg5+
{ 21.Rxc3 ?  Qxc3  22.h3  with the idea of Rd3 looks promising as well, but Black has a defence.  Qc2 !  23.Rd3  Ne4 !  -+  and with g3 protected and h3 blocked White has no threats. }
4... Kh7 5. Nxf7 Qxg5 { 22...Nd5  23.Qh6+  Kg8  24.Qg6# } 6. Nxg5+ Kg6 7. Rxc3
{ White has a rook and two pawns for two pieces. With his active rooks he can attack Black's weak king, the weak e6-pawn and Black's queenside. He will win at least another pawn and is clearly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Huerta Martinez, Alberto vs. Neiman, Emmanuel"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2r4/ppkn1Q1p/2pb1pp1/3p1B2/7q/P1N1B2P/1PP2PP1/3R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g3
{ This deep move can best be understood after first calculating the obvious try   21.Rd4  after which Black has two good replies.  Qh5   21...Qxd4  is also good enough for equality.  22.Bxd4  gxf5  23.Qxh7 =  and now the desirable  22.Bg4  fails to  (Qe5 -+) }
1... Bxg3
{ 21...Qc4  22.Bd3  +-   21...Qh5  22.Bg4  Qe5  23.Bf4  Qe8  24.Nxd5+  cxd5  25.Bxd6+  Kxd6  26.Qxd5+  Kc7   26...Ke7  27.Re1+  Ne5  28.Qe6+  Kf8  29.Qxf6+  +-  27.Qd6+  Kc8  28.Rd4  +- }
2. Rd4 { After luring the bishop to g3 this now wins. } 2... Qh5
{ With the bishop on g3   22...Qxd4  isn't really an option.  23.Bxd4  gxf5  24.fxg3  +- }
3. Bg4 { 23.Nxd5+  cxd5  24.Bg4  transposes } 3... Qe5
{ with the bishop in fron of the queen there are no threats against White's king and they win with }
4. Nxd5+ cxd5 5. Rxd5 Qe8 6. Rc5+ Kb8 7. Qxe8 Rxe8 8. Bxd7 Rd8 9. fxg3
{ Finally another idea of 1. g3. The bishop will hang in some variations. } *

